     THREE SURFACES
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="surfaces">
  <div class="cge-container">
    <p class="cge-section-label fade-in">The Core Concept</p>
    <h2 class="section-title fade-in">The three surfaces of Copilot in Excel</h2>
    <p class="section-intro fade-in">New users get confused because Copilot shows up in three different places that behave differently. Learn the distinction once and everything else clicks.</p>

    <div class="comparison-wrapper fade-in">
      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Surface</th><th>What it is</th><th>Best for</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>The Copilot pane</td><td>The agentic side panel ("Let's edit your workbook"). You chat in natural language; Copilot can plan and edit the whole workbook.</td><td>Multi-step work, analysis, building tables/charts, summaries, "do this for me" requests.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>The =COPILOT() function</td><td>AI you type into a cell like a formula. It returns results into the grid and recalculates when its inputs change.</td><td>Row-by-row tasks at scale: classify, summarize, extract, draft, score — repeated down a column.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Inline cell / range actions</td><td>Right-click or the sparkle on a selection for quick suggestions (formulas, formatting, insights) in context.</td><td>Fast, in-the-moment help on a specific cell or range without composing a full prompt.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="callout callout-note fade-in">
      <div class="callout-title">🧭 The mental model</div>
      The <strong>pane</strong> is conversational and can change many things — use it to <em>build something once</em>. The <strong>=COPILOT() function</strong> lives in the grid and runs per-row — use it to <em>apply AI to every row</em> of a dataset.
    </div>

    <div class="screenshot-placeholder fade-in">
      <span class="ss-icon">📸</span>
