<section id="modes">
  <div class="cge-container">
    <p class="cge-section-label fade-in">The Controls</p>
    <h2 class="section-title fade-in">Modes, models &amp; one-time setup</h2>
    <p class="section-intro fade-in">Four controls decide how Copilot behaves: the working mode, the model, the + menu, and your standing preferences (Workbook Rules + Personalization). Learn these and you control trust, quality, and consistency.</p>

    <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem; margin:1rem 0;" class="fade-in">Working modes — the most important control for trust</h3>
    <div class="comparison-wrapper fade-in">
      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Mode</th><th>What the menu says</th><th>When to use it</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>✏️ Allow editing</td><td>"Copilot can edit your document directly."</td><td>Trusted, well-understood transforms on a copy of your data. Fastest, most hands-off.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>📋 Plan</td><td>"Come up with a plan before editing."</td><td>High-stakes or multi-step work. Review and approve the plan before anything changes. Maximum control.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>💬 Chat only</td><td>"Copilot will respond in chat only."</td><td>Analysis, explanations, and learning with zero risk of changing the file. Safest for exploration.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-tip fade-in">
      <div class="callout-title">💡 Tip</div>
      Default to <strong>Plan</strong> mode while you build trust. Once you've seen Copilot handle a task type well a few times, switch that task to <strong>Allow editing</strong> for speed.
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warn fade-in">
      <div class="callout-title">⚠️ Always</div>
      Even in Allow editing mode, work on a <strong>copy</strong> of important data and verify results. <strong>Ctrl+Z</strong> undoes any Copilot change.
    </div>

    <div class="screenshot-placeholder fade-in">
      <span class="ss-icon">📸</span>
      <span style="font-weight:600;color:var(--text-primary);font-size:0.95rem;">The mode dropdown</span>
      <span>Expanded "Allow editing ▾" menu showing the three options with their descriptions.</span>
      <span style="font-family:var(--font-mono);font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--accent);">SUGGESTED SOURCE: your mode-dropdown screenshot</span>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:1.25rem; margin:2.5rem 0 1rem;" class="fade-in">Choosing a model</h3>
    <div class="comparison-wrapper fade-in">
      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Option</th><th>Guidance</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Auto <span style="color:var(--text-meta);font-size:0.8rem;">(default)</span></td><td>Copilot automatically selects the best model for your task. Leave it here unless you have a specific reason to change.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>GPT-5.4 / GPT-5.5 <span style="color:var(--text-meta);font-size:0.8rem;">(OpenAI)</span></td><td>Strong general reasoning and broad capability; 5.5 is newer. Good all-rounders for analysis and drafting.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Claude Opus 4.7 / 4.8 <span style="color:var(--text-meta);font-size:0.8rem;">(Anthropic)</span></td><td>Excellent at careful, structured reasoning, long instructions, and nuanced writing; 4.8 is newest. Great for complex, rules-heavy, or narrative tasks.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-note fade-in">
      <div class="callout-title">📝 Note</div>
      Models change over time as new versions ship. If unsure, <strong>Auto</strong> is the safe choice. Model choice rarely fixes a bad prompt — a clear, specific request improves results far more.
    </div>

    <div class="screenshot-placeholder fade-in">
