<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════
     =COPILOT() FUNCTION
     ═══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="function">
  <div class="cge-container">
    <p class="cge-section-label fade-in">The Function</p>
    <h2 class="section-title fade-in">The =COPILOT() function</h2>
    <p class="section-intro fade-in">=COPILOT() brings AI into the formula bar. Type it like any function; it sends your instruction plus optional cell references to the model and returns the result into the grid — recalculating automatically when its inputs change. Ideal for applying AI to every row of a dataset.</p>

    <div style="max-width:760px;margin:0 auto;">
      <span class="prompt-label">Function signature</span>
      <div class="prompt-text" onclick="copyPrompt(this)" style="font-family:var(--font-mono);">=COPILOT(prompt_part1, [context1], prompt_part2, [context2], …)<span class="copy-hint">Click to copy</span></div>
      <p style="color:var(--text-secondary);font-size:0.9rem;margin:1rem 0;">You alternate plain-language instruction with ranges of data. The text says <em>what to do</em>; the ranges say <em>what to do it to</em>. Results can be a single value or spill across cells.</p>

      <h3 style="font-size:1.15rem;margin:1.5rem 0 0.75rem;" class="fade-in">Worked examples — click any to copy</h3>
      <div class="prompt-text" onclick="copyPrompt(this)" style="font-family:var(--font-mono);">=COPILOT("Classify this ticket as Billing, Technical, or Account: ", A2)<span class="copy-hint">Click to copy</span></div>
      <div class="prompt-text" onclick="copyPrompt(this)" style="font-family:var(--font-mono);margin-top:0.6rem;">=COPILOT("Summarize in 5 words or fewer: ", B2)<span class="copy-hint">Click to copy</span></div>
      <div class="prompt-text" onclick="copyPrompt(this)" style="font-family:var(--font-mono);margin-top:0.6rem;">=COPILOT("Return only the city name from this address: ", D2)<span class="copy-hint">Click to copy</span></div>
      <div class="prompt-text" onclick="copyPrompt(this)" style="font-family:var(--font-mono);margin-top:0.6rem;">=COPILOT("Label each row Positive, Neutral, or Negative: ", E2:E500)<span class="copy-hint">Click to copy</span></div>
      <div class="prompt-text" onclick="copyPrompt(this)" style="font-family:var(--font-mono);margin-top:0.6rem;">=COPILOT("Write a one-sentence thank-you to this customer: ", F2, " about their order of ", G2)<span class="copy-hint">Click to copy</span></div>
    </div>

    <h3 style="font-size:1.15rem;margin:2rem 0 0.75rem;" class="fade-in">Function vs. pane — which to use</h3>
    <div class="comparison-wrapper fade-in">
      <table class="comparison-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Use =COPILOT() when…</th><th>Use the pane when…</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>You need the same AI task repeated down a column (classify, summarize, extract, score).</td><td>You're doing one-off, multi-step work (build a report, analyze, chart).</td></tr>
          <tr><td>You want the result to live in the grid and recalc as data changes.</td><td>You want a conversation, explanation, or a plan you approve.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>You're enriching a dataset for further analysis.</td><td>You're transforming or restructuring the workbook itself.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="callout callout-warn fade-in">
      <div class="callout-title">⚠️ Language tasks, not math</div>
      =COPILOT() is for classify / summarize / extract / draft / reason-over-text — <strong>not</strong> precise math. For totals, rates, and lookups use real formulas (SUM, XLOOKUP). AI output is generated, so spot-check. On large ranges, sample ~10 rows first, confirm quality, then fill down.
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

